\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid Take a secret phrase and apply Shamir Secret Sharing to encode it into n secret phrases.\par
\par
Using Shamir Secret Sharing, a secret phrase with "nw" words can be encoded into n secret phrases,\par
each with "nw" words as well. Before encoding, a threshold parameter t (with t<=n) is defined, so \par
that only t shares are required for the reconstruction of the original secret. (To reconstruct the\par
secret, use the script reconstruct.py provided in this package.)\par
\par
\par
Requisites\par
----------\par
1) Before running this script, a dictionary of words to encode secret phrases, with the name\par
"wordlist.txt", must be provided in the same folder as the script. This dictionary must:\par
    * Have 2^nb words, where nb is an integer (so that each word represents an nb-bit number)\par
    * Be a .txt file where each line has a single word.\par
\par
This package comes pre-loaded with BIP-39's 2048-word dictionary.\par
\par
2) The secret phrase to be shared should:\par
    * Have between 3 and 60 words.\par
    * Have only words that are contained in the dictionary "wordlist.txt".\par
    * Be written in a single line, with each word separated by only a space.\par
\par
By default, the secret that will be encoded is read from a .txt file called "secret.txt", to be\par
located in the same folder as this script. (The secret may also be provided right in the command line\par
at execution--see below).\par
\par
\par
Execution and inputs\par
--------------------\par
This script should be called from the command line, with the following mandatory inputs (flags):\par
\par
-n: (integer) Number of shares that will be generated from the secret phrase.\par
-t, --threshold: (integer) Minimum number of shares that will be required at reconstruction.\par
\par
The following flags are optional:\par
\par
-s, --secret: (string) Allows for either of the following options:\par
    * Specify the secret phrase directly on the command line.\par
    * Specify a custom file path to a .txt file with the secret.\par
    (In either case, the secret must abide by the same format considerations stated above)\par
-v, --verbose: If this flag is used, the generated shares are verbose (see "outputs" below.)\par
\par
\par
Outputs\par
-------\par
During execution, the /shares folder is emptied, and its contents are replaced with the following \par
JSON files:\par
\par
* reconstruction_data.json: Contains the following entries:\par
    - total_shares: Number of shares n generated during encoding\par
    - threshold: Threshold t representing the minimum number of shares needed for reconstruction.\par
    - primitive_poly: Primitive polynomial used to generate the Galois field used for encryption;\par
      necessary for decryption. For more details, please read modules/shamir.py\par
    - dictionary: A copy of the contents of the dictionary wordlist.txt\par
\par
* share_i.json (for 1<=i<=n): Contains the following entries:\par
    - id: ID number i, with 1<=i<=n, identifying the share.\par
    - share: list of words, one of the n secret phrases that the original secret was encoded into.\par
    Remark: if the --verbose flag was used at runtime, each of the JSON shares will also contain the\par
    reconstruction data.\par
\par
The shares are also printed on the command line.\par
}
 \par
}}
